<treatment ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6267517" ID-GBIF-Taxon="100118995" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6267517" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:23E718CD934139126342E70807626D89" httpUri="http://treatment.plazi.org/id/23E718CD934139126342E70807626D89" lastPageNumber="11" pageNumber="11">
<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="11">
In the present study five specimens of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1777C8AB-2B34-4D3A-B12B-89E47F051D6B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Derichthyidae" genus="Derichthys" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Derichthys serpentinus Gill 1884:433" order="Anguilliformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="serpentinus">Derichthys serpentinus</taxonomicName>
Gill were collected during the spring and autumn cruises (Figure 16). They occurred along the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vitória-Trindade">Vitoria-Trindade</normalizedToken>
ridge over the seamounts Jaseur and Almirante Saldanha. This species can be easily distinguished from the other two because it has fewer than 100 preanal myomeres (Smith, 1989g). Although 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1777C8AB-2B34-4D3A-B12B-89E47F051D6B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Derichthyidae" genus="Derichthys" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Derichthys serpentinus Gill 1884:433" order="Anguilliformes" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="serpentinus">D. serpentinus</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed through the Atlantic Ocean (Smith, 1989g), it has never been recorded for Brazil. It was not possible to count the myomeres of the smallest leptocephali. Study Material: DZUFRJ 2811, 2812, 2846; five specimens; preanal myomeres 67-83; predorsal myomeres 45-50; LVBV myomeres 59-61; total myomeres ca 125; 11.5-55.0 mm SL.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
